      <h2>The 6 deductions on every US paycheck</h2>

      <h3>1. Federal Income Tax</h3>
      <p>The biggest deduction for most workers. The US uses a progressive bracket system — you pay higher rates only on income above each threshold, not on everything. 2025 brackets for single filers range from 10% (income up to $11,925) to 37% (above $626,350).</p>
      <p>Standard deduction for 2025: $15,750 (single), $31,500 (married filing jointly). This reduces your taxable income before brackets apply.</p>

      <h3>2. Social Security Tax (6.2%)</h3>
      <p>Funds Social Security retirement benefits. Rate is 6.2% of wages up to $176,100 in 2025. Your employer matches this amount. Once you earn over $176,100 in a year, Social Security stops being withheld.</p>

      <h3>3. Medicare Tax (1.45%)</h3>
      <p>Funds Medicare healthcare for seniors. Rate is 1.45% with no income cap — you pay this on every dollar earned. An additional 0.9% applies to income over $200,000 (single) or $250,000 (married).</p>

      <h3>4. State Income Tax (0–13.3%)</h3>
      <p>Varies wildly by state. Nine states have zero state income tax. California tops the list at 13.3% on high incomes. Most states fall in the 3–7% range. This is often the easiest tax to reduce — by living in a lower-tax state.</p>

      <h3>5. 401k Contribution (optional, pre-tax)</h3>
      <p>Traditional 401k contributions reduce your taxable income. Contributing $6,000/year in the 22% bracket saves $1,320 in federal taxes. 2025 limit: $23,500 ($31,000 if age 50+). Many employers match 3–6% — always contribute enough to get the full match.</p>

      <h3>6. Health Insurance Premium</h3>
      <p>Your share of employer health plan costs. Usually pre-tax, reducing your taxable income. Median annual employee contribution: $1,800 (single) to $6,000 (family).</p>

